---

<Layout title={guideData.title} description={guideData.description}>
  <!-- FAQ Structured Data -->
  <StructuredData
    type="FAQPage"
    data={[
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the best AI website builder for real estate agents?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "For individual real estate agents, Mixo ($9/month) is the best choice with unbeatable value for budget-conscious agents, effective lead capture forms, property showcase capabilities, and mobile optimization essential for house-hunters on-the-go. Framer excels for real estate teams wanting modern design quality (9.5/10), beautiful property galleries that load quickly despite heavy photo content, team profile pages, and impressive presentation that stands out. Webflow serves brokerages needing powerful CMS for agent directories, property databases, advanced search functionality, and complete control for complex real estate websites. Squarespace is ideal for property managers with professional listing presentations, beautiful photo galleries, and polished design that elevates property perception. Individual agents should start with Mixo for value and simplicity, teams should choose Framer for design impact, brokerages should invest in Webflow for powerful capabilities, property managers should consider Squarespace for professional presentation."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What should real estate websites include?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Real estate websites need: (1) Home page with featured listings, search functionality, and immediate lead capture, (2) Property detail pages with 20+ professional photos, virtual tours/video, complete property specs, neighborhood information, map location, schedule viewing CTA, (3) Agent or team profile page with professional photo, bio, sales track record, client testimonials, areas served, (4) Buying/selling process page explaining what to expect and step-by-step guidance, (5) Market data or blog with local updates, property values, neighborhood guides, (6) Contact page with multiple contact methods, consultation booking, property valuation form, office location. Essential: professional photo galleries, mobile optimization (70%+ searches on mobile), fast loading despite heavy images, lead capture forms, virtual tours increasingly expected. Position yourself as local expert, not just another agent."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do real estate agents handle MLS/IDX integration?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Real estate agents have four options for MLS/IDX integration: (1) Full MLS/IDX integration using 10Web with MLS plugin or WordPress with IDX plugins - provides direct database connection with always-current listings and automatic updates but costs more ($50-200/month) and requires technical setup. Best for brokerages with budget. (2) Manual property entry - complete control and no extra fees but time-consuming and requires manual updates. Best for individual agents with fewer listings. (3) Third-party tools like Showcase, RealtyFeed, or MLS Advantage - automated updates with easier integration but monthly fees and limited customization. Best for agents wanting automation without complexity. (4) Hybrid approach - featured listings manual plus MLS search widget, offering best of both worlds with control over featured listings while providing MLS search capability. Most individual agents start with manual entry or hybrid approach, upgrading to full integration as business grows. Focus on professional presentation of your best listings rather than comprehensive MLS database."
        }
      }
    ]}
  />

